<SubSubSection title="First Moment of Area: Centroid of an Area" id="first-moi">
The first moment of the area A with respect to the z-axis is given by <InlineEquation equation='Q_x = \\int_A y dA = \\Sigma yA' /> .

 The first moment of the area A with respect to the y-axis is given by <InlineEquation equation='Q_y = \\int_A x dA  = \\Sigma zA' />.



 <InlineEquation equation='(\\overline{x}, \\overline{y})' title="The centroid of an area." background="True"/>

<Image src='/sol/bending/Centroid.png' width='2'> Centroid of a body </Image>

<DisplayEquation equation='\\bar{x} = \\frac{1}{A}\\int_A x dA\\' title="x coordinate." background="True"/>
<DisplayEquation equation='\\bar{y} = \\frac{1}{A}\\int_A y dA\\' title="y coordinate." background="True"/> 

Complex (or composite) areas can be divided into smaller, easier parts.

<Image src='/sol/bending/CompositeCentroid.png' width='6'>  Centroid of a composite body</Image>

<DisplayEquation equation="\\bar{X} = \\frac{1}{A_{tot}}\\sum_i (A_i\\bar{y}_i)\\" title="Composite x coordinate" background="True"/>
<DisplayEquation equation='\\bar{Y} = \\frac{1}{A_{tot}} \\sum_i (A_i\\bar{y}_i)' title="Composite y coordinate" background="True"/>




</SubSubSection>

